113.content:
Roblox: Ninja Legensd Flyhack made by GalaxyLeasco

_G.FLYING = false
local LP = game:service('Players').LocalPlayer
local T = LP.Character.UpperTorso
local CONTROL = {F = 0, B = 0, L = 0, R = 0}
local lCONTROL = {F = 0, B = 0, L = 0, R = 0}
local SPEED = 5
local MOUSE = LP:GetMouse()


local function FLY()
_G.FLYING = true
local BG = Instance.new('BodyGyro', T)
local BV = Instance.new('BodyVelocity', T)
BG.P = 9e4
BG.maxTorque = Vector3.new(9e9, 9e9, 9e9)
BG.cframe = T.CFrame
BV.velocity = Vector3.new(0, 0.1, 0)
BV.maxForce = Vector3.new(9e9, 9e9, 9e9)


spawn(function()
repeat wait()
LP.Character.Humanoid.PlatformStand = true
if CONTROL.L + CONTROL.R ~= 0 or CONTROL.F + CONTROL.B ~= 0 then
SPEED = 50
elseif not (CONTROL.L + CONTROL.R ~= 0 or CONTROL.F + CONTROL.B ~= 0) and SPEED ~= 0 then
SPEED = 0
end
if (CONTROL.L + CONTROL.R) ~= 0 or (CONTROL.F + CONTROL.B) ~= 0 then
BV.velocity = ((game.Workspace.CurrentCamera.CoordinateFrame.lookVector * (CONTROL.F + CONTROL.B)) + ((game.Workspace.CurrentCamera.CoordinateFrame * CFrame.new(CONTROL.L + CONTROL.R, (CONTROL.F + CONTROL.B) * 0.2, 0).p) - game.Workspace.CurrentCamera.CoordinateFrame.p)) * SPEED
lCONTROL = {F = CONTROL.F, B = CONTROL.B, L = CONTROL.L, R = CONTROL.R}
elseif (CONTROL.L + CONTROL.R) == 0 and (CONTROL.F + CONTROL.B) == 0 and SPEED ~= 0 then
BV.velocity = ((game.Workspace.CurrentCamera.CoordinateFrame.lookVector * (lCONTROL.F + lCONTROL.B)) + ((game.Workspace.CurrentCamera.CoordinateFrame * CFrame.new(lCONTROL.L + lCONTROL.R, (lCONTROL.F + lCONTROL.B) * 0.2, 0).p) - game.Workspace.CurrentCamera.CoordinateFrame.p)) * SPEED
else
BV.velocity = Vector3.new(0, 0.1, 0)
end
BG.cframe = game.Workspace.CurrentCamera.CoordinateFrame
until not _G.FLYING
CONTROL = {F = 0, B = 0, L = 0, R = 0}
lCONTROL = {F = 0, B = 0, L = 0, R = 0}
SPEED = 0
BG:destroy()
BV:destroy()
LP.Character.Humanoid.PlatformStand = false
end)
end

MOUSE.KeyDown:connect(function(KEY)
if KEY:lower() == 'w' then
CONTROL.F = 1
elseif KEY:lower() == 's' then
CONTROL.B = -1
elseif KEY:lower() == 'a' then
CONTROL.L = -1
elseif KEY:lower() == 'd' then
CONTROL.R = 1
end
end)

MOUSE.KeyUp:connect(function(KEY)
if KEY:lower() == 'w' then
CONTROL.F = 0
elseif KEY:lower() == 's' then
CONTROL.B = 0
elseif KEY:lower() == 'a' then
CONTROL.L = 0
elseif KEY:lower() == 'd' then
CONTROL.R = 0
end
end)




FLY()

function check_and_dig(block_name)
    local s
    local data
    
    while true do
        s, data = turtle.inspect()
        if s and data["name"] == block_name then
            turtle.dig()
            turtle.forward()
            return
        end
    end
end

bn = "botania:livingrock"

check_and_dig(bn)

for j=1,3 do
    for i=1,2 do
        check_and_dig(bn)
    end
    turtle.turnLeft()
end

check_and_dig(bn)
turtle.forward()
turtle.turnLeft()
turtle.back()

print("Done")

-- private use of Pirmax's ComputerCraft Turtle code of a tree farm

while true do

turtle.select(16)
if turtle.compareDown() == true then
turtle.turnRight()
end

turtle.select(15)
if turtle.compareDown() == true then
	turtle.turnRight()
	--sleep(2)
	turtle.select(13)
	if turtle.compare() == true then
		i = 1
		while i <= 6 do
			turtle.select(3)
			turtle.dig()
			turtle.select(2)
			turtle.digUp()
			turtle.up()
			i = i + 1
		end
		i = 1
		while i <= 6 do
			turtle.down()
			i = i + 1
		end
	end
	turtle.select(2)
	turtle.place()
	turtle.turnLeft()
end

if turtle.getFuelAmount() <= 200 then
	print("Il manque du carburant !")
	turtle.select(10)
	turtle.placeUp()

	for i = 3, 12 do
		turtle.select(i)
		turtle.dropUp()
	end

	turtle.select(16)
	turtle.dropUp()
	turtle.select(15)
	turtle.dropUp()
	turtle.select(14)
	turtle.dropUp()
	turtle.select(13)
	turtle.dropUp()

	turtle.select(2)
	turtle.dropUp()

	turtle.select(1)
	turtle.suckUp(16)
	turtle.craft()
	turtle.refuel(64)

	-- Process inverse

	for i = 3, 12 do
		turtle.select(i)
		turtle.suckUp()
	end

	turtle.select(16)
	turtle.suckUp()
	turtle.select(15)
	turtle.suckUp()
	turtle.select(14)
	turtle.suckUp()
	turtle.select(13)
	turtle.suckUp()

	turtle.select(2)
	turtle.suckUp()

end

turtle.select(14)
if turtle.compareDown() == true then
turtle.turnRight()
turtle.select(3)
turtle.drop()
turtle.turnLeft()
turtle.turnLeft()
turtle.select(1)
turtle.suck()
turtle.refuel(turtle.getItemCount(1))
turtle.turnRight()
end
        
turtle.forward()

end

160.name: Untitled
160.content:
[Patch]

; Info: Completely disable Skyrim's memory allocator and use regular C malloc. That means memory blocks will not exist anymore
;       and game will not crash at some arbitrary limit. Theoretically it should also be faster (especially loading screens)
;       and eliminate most ILS or freezing issues.
; IMPORTANT!!: You NEED custom plugin loader to run this so CrashFixPlugin.dll gets loaded before the game initializes!
;              Here is the link to "SKSE Plugin Preloader": http://www.nexusmods.com/skyrim/mods/75795/?
; When this is enabled then Safety Load and SSME/SKSE memory patch are not needed, but they don't cause any trouble if you do have them.
UseOSAllocators=1

; Info: When the game crashes unexpectedly then write the relevant information from crash to Data/SKSE/Plugins/CrashLog/crash_time.txt
;       If game crashes when running out of memory or has other issues it's possible for the file to not appear or become empty!
;       If the game crashes in SKSE dll or a SKSE plugin dll then it's possible for the crash information to not appear.
;       This setting's value is treated as flags where:
;       1 - enabled (TL;DR set this for normal enable)
;       2 - don't write timestamp into file name but instead always write to crash_last.txt (overwritten by default)
;       4 - don't ignore already known crashes, usually ones that display a message box are ignored
;       8 - append file if it already exists instead of replacing
;       16 - when the game crashes CTD without a message box about game stopped responding
RecordCrashInfo=1

; Write messages that appear in error box also to file in "Data/SKSE/Plugins/CrashFixPluginLog.txt"
LogMessageToFile=1

; Info: Warn user on startup if ENB settings are incorrect.
WarnBadENB=1

; Info: Crash happens unknown constructor (TESObjectLAND::unk_24 object), movaps instruction is used
;       but heap allocate did not allocate this object to have 16 align. Crash happens more frequently
;       with high Ugrids because more cells are loaded and greater chance to misalign.
; Solution: Could align only this object or align all objects. Trying with all to see what happens since
;       same error could be elsewhere as well and I think I have seen it elsewhere.
; Result: Fixes these type of crashes. Some people report longer loading times and higher memory usage with this enabled!
; Update: Disabled by default since it's incompatible with some ENB settings, higher memory usage and longer loading times.
;         It's safe and probably good to enable if you are ok with those downsides. I have not personally experienced
;         any incompatibility with ENB, some people say it messes up their game that's why I wrote it here.
AlignHeapAllocate=1

; Info: Game crashes when strcmp is passed NULL char*
; Address: D573A8
; Cause: Most frequently happens in TthkbClipGenerator::activate (0xBF2FB3),
;        tracked issue to skeleton was deleted in another thread while
;        this function is attempting to use it. Have seen in other places
;        too.
; Solution: Unknown. This doesn't really fix it for BF2FB3 because it just pops up in foot IK.
;        If patched in foot IK it pops up in hand IK, the problem is larger than just this.
;        Still enabled because it may fix crashes in other places too this is a very common function.
;        There's really no reason not to have it since the game would crash certainly with this off.
; Enable one. NoTry may be slightly faster but catches less crashes.
StrCmp=1
;StrCmpNoTry=1

; Info: Game crashes when strlen is used on NULL char*
; Address: 46EDF0
; Cause: NiNode names are compared, one of the NiNode's name is NULL.
; Code:
;	NiNode ** v72 = NiNode::children.data - this is iterated until count
;	NiNode * v69 = ...
;	const char * v56 = v69->name;
;	if ( v56 )
;	{
;	const char * v57 = v72[v49]->name; // <- v57 name is not checked for NULL for some reason ?
;	_strnicmp(v56, v57, strlen(v57)); <- strlen on NULL, also result is not even used anywhere!
;	}
; Solution: Unknown, temporarily bypass whole strcmp since it's unused.
; Result: Seems to have stopped the crash for me.
StrLen=1

; Info: Unknown, reported as loading save game.
; Address: 8B437C - vtable seems to be 0 or wrong pointer is used.
; Solution: Skip since this is the last part of the function and already has a check anyway
UnkUniqueId=1

; Info: Unknown, reported as loading save game. Possibly related to rendering. First
;       argument is gNiDX9Renderer->unk_650 which is a pointer.
; Address: CEC5EC - null pointer is passed as second argument to function, this function does not expect it
; Solution: Bypass using argument if it's null. Maybe doesn't fix.
Render650=1

; Info: Unknown, no info was provided. // char __thiscall TESObjectREFR::unk_4D4EB0(TESObjectREFR *this)
; Address: 4D4EB9 - vtable of base form is 0
; Solution: Bypass and pretend that base form is 0 since the function does this check itself already
UnkObjRef4D4EB0=1

; Info: Game is saving location's seen data to save game. The data is NULL.
; Address: 4C6031
; Cause: Game doesn't check for null pointer
; Code:
; TESObjectCELL * v3 = ...
; v5 = BaseExtraList::GetSeenData_40D980(&v3->extraData);
; result = (void *)(*((int (__thiscall **)(_DWORD, _DWORD))*v5 + 1))(v5, v2); // <-- v5 can be null! but not checked
; v5 is IntSeenData, size is known.
; Solution: Only solution seems to be temporarily creating an empty IntSeenData and writing this to stream instead.
NullSeenData=1

; Info: BSFixedString::Set is called with NULL argument.
; Address: A51285
; Solution: Ignore call when NULL argument. Not really a solution :P probably better than crashing though.
StringRefSetNull=1

; Info: This crash happens because StrLen crash was prevented.
; Address: 46EE1D
; Solution: Skip over it.
; Result: See StrLen.
SkipStrLenCrash=1

; Info: This crash happens because unknown reasons during loading. Something to do with behavior graph.
;       One of the more common crashes I get.
; Address: C27A8F
; Solution: Don't know, trying to let game think the value is 0 and see what happens.
; Result: Haven't had this crash since.
bhvGraphUpdateLoad=1

; Info: Crash happens during loading, no idea. Might be related to rendering.
; Address: D822D8
; Solution: Tried patch something but it probably doesn't work.
Unk11=1

; Info: Incompatible skeleton, but could be something else too.
; Address: 46ECF5 - NiNode children access
; Solution: No solution from here, but since it's going to crash anyway we could at least
;           warn user about possible incompatible skeleton and let them fix it. Shows messagebox
MissingNode=1

; Info: Crash, it's function array and index goes out of bounds which causes it to call invalid address.
; Address: 6F3A31
; Solution: Check index before calling.
; Result: Haven't had this crash since.
IndexError1=1

; Info: Crash happens in "MovementPlannerAgentWarp" function, unknown what it does. LookupFormById returns
;       NULL and game does not check or expect this to happen.
; Address: 76E358
; Solution: Game has a check for if returned isn't actor it sets 0 as value, we will do same if NULL is returned.
MovementPlannerAgentWarp=1

; Info: Crash happens in DDB0A0, seems to be used in some havok animated object's vtables.
;       Normally these crashes are fixed by aligning allocated memory with 16 bytes. But
;       this one isn't because it can be used on static memory locations which aren't using
;       Skyrim's allocator at all, this means that memory isn't guaranteed to be 16 byte aligned.
; Address: DDB0B2
; Solution: Use movups instruction instead of movaps.
UnallocatedMovaps=1

; Info: Weird crash with NULL ptr in TESWorldSpace::GetCellByCoordMask_4375D0, don't know why it happens.
; Address: 437604
; Solution: return 0 if this crash would happen.
; Result: Haven't had this crash since, but it's rare anyway so it could be coincidence.
CellNullCrash=1

; Info: Crash when trying to do: v14 = MagicItem::unk_406C70(a3)->properties.projectile;
;       This 406C70 function is something like "GetMainMagicEffect". Sometimes though it may return
;       NULL and in 90% of places the game expects this and checks for NULL result, this patch will
;       fix the remaining locations.
; Address: 7E39EC, 657677, 6577D5, 65FEEC, 8127CF
; Solution: Check for NULL and skip (depends on location) if it is.
GetMainMagicEffect=1

; Info: Crash when game searches node "NPC COM [COM ]" on actor but the node was not found. This is unexpected
;       for game because it uses the result without checking for NULL. This whole thing has something to do
;       with mounting. The function that does this whole thing is present in "StopMountCameraHandler" and
;       "MountInteraction" vtable. Also it seems that this has something to do with updating position.
; More info: Was reported that this could happen if non-humanoid tries to mount a horse. This is a rather specific
;            error with a mod. Instead we will show error message to user when this happens so they can
;            fix or uninstall that mod.
; Address: 6E7F85
; Solution: Check for NULL and if it is NULL then use base node of actor instead of this. It's fine because
;           we only take X and Y position from it.
; Solution2: Show error message and crash after.
MountNodeCrash=0
MountNodeWarn=1

; Info: Crash when game is trying to setup foot IK but there's a problem. Real cause is unknown but for me.
;       So we will display a message box when this crash happens. Seems related to the
;       StrCmp crash in BF2FB3, maybe. Try reducing the amount of installed animations.
; Address: BFECC1
; Solution: No solution from here, display warning with helpful tips.
IKCrashWarn=1

; Info: Crash happens when rendering and saving. I think this is when it renders the save game image.
; if ( v8 ) // <- not null
; {
;  if ( v8 )
;    v9 = *(v8 + 8); // <- *(v8 + 8) is null
;  else
;    v9 = 0;
;  v10 = *(v9 + 140) * *(a2 + 4) // <- crash because null
;    + *(v9 + 136) * *a2
;    + *(v9 + 144) * *(a2 + 8);
;  v21 = v10 - *(*(v8 + 8) + 148) * a3;
; }
; Address: CB051A
; Solution: We will skip this if block when *(v8 + 8) is null, as if v8 was null.
RenderSave=1

; Info: Crash was reported as casting spell. Only happens sometimes. Happens in movement controller.
;       Seems like vtable is NULL.
; Address: 76636B
; Solution: This happens in a for loop and it happens in if clause. We can skip if this crash would happen.
MoveControllerCast=1

; Info: Crash when saving game and trying to render (possibly save game image again?). It's trying to get
;       vtable of NULL pointer which will crash.
;   if ((*a2 + 76)(a2, a1)) // a2 is null
;   {
;     *(0x1BA9344) = a1;
;     *(0x1BA9340) = a2;
;   }
;   else
;   {
;     *(0x1BA9340) = 0;
;     *(0x1BA9344) = 0;
;   }
; Address: CAF9F7
; Solution: Skip function call and set return value to false so we don't have to use the NULL value.
SaveRenderCrash=1

; Info: Crash when game tries to get loaded node but it is set to NULL. Only ever seen this on two people.
;       It is most likely actually related to corrupted mesh being unable to be loaded and game does not expect it.
;       NiNode * node = a->GetLoadedStateNiNode();
;       v2 = node->(*(vtable+0x14))(); // <- node is NULL
;       if(v2) { *((int*)(v2 + 212)) = 0; } // <- we can skip this part since it has a check anyway
; Address: 4C119E
; Solution: Real solution would be to find the broken mesh and remove it. So lets notify user instead of ignoring this part.
; Enable one of the following, ignore problem and try to continue or show message box with object reference form ID and form Type.
NullLoadedNodeIgnore=0
NullLoadedNodeNotify=1

; Info: Crash in GarbageCollector::Add when actor argument's base form is NULL. Game does not check this, when in
;       some other places it does check for this possibility.
; Address: 690A69
NullActorBaseForm=1

; Info: Crash when modifying actor value but the pointer is bad, possibly due to actor being invalid. This happens often
;       when script engine is lagged and spells want to modify actor values a lot.
; Address: 6E07C6
AVSetCrash=1

; Info: If your scripts use more than 65535 different strings then the save game will be corrupt and not possible to load.
;       This fixes it by changing the save file format slightly if string count is higher than 65520. That means if you
;       have this option enabled and your save game would have become corrupt it changes format instead and vanilla game
;       or save game tools will not be able to open it! Opposite is true as well, if the count goes below 65520 after
;       and you save again then the format reverts to vanilla.
; TLDR: Fix for https://forums.nexusmods.com/index.php?/topic/3924850-corrupt-saves-strcount-0xffff-ctd-on-load/
; Address: Around 30 different parts of code had to be patched.
StringCount32=1

; Info: Warn if SKSE memory patch is not active. This checks if default heap size is 256 or less and warns if you try to
;       click New, Continue or Load in main menu. Still lets you play the game, just shows a warning.
WarnSKSEMemoryPatch=1

; Info: If AlignHeapAllocate is disabled by user then fix that one movaps crash manually. There's no downside to having this enabled.
; Address: 4BD832
FixMovApsManuallyIfAlignedAllocateIsDisabled=1

; Info: Overwrite array allocator directly when UseOSAllocators is set to 1. Don't understand the code enough yet to
;       say if it's safe or not. At this point it's just here for testing.
OverwriteArrayAllocator=0

; Info: Player's NiNode (not necessarily same as loaded node) is NULL while drawing world.
; Address: 69B84B
NullPlayerNode=1

; Info: Function TESObjectREFR::CanBeMoved_4D9CF0 is called on an object reference that has NULL base form. This is not expected
;       and will crash. We will instead return false from that function if that's the case. The problem is most likely larger than
;       just this, if you prefer to crash instead disable it.
; Address: 4D9D09
NullBaseFormMove=1

; Info: Game tries to iterate child nodes of a NiAVObject but it's possible that the target is not a NiNode and can't have child nodes.
;       This ends up in a NULL pointer crash.
;  v26 = v22->vtable->sub_5EADD0(v22); // Returns "this" if v22 is a NiNode and returns "NULL" if not.
;  for ( i = 0; i < v26->children.emptyRunStart; ++i ) // crash because v26 is NULL.
; Address: 46CA06
NullRefNode=1

; Info: Something is done with outfit of NPC, but one or more entry is NULL and game crashes.
; Address: 561FF7
NullOutfitEntry=1

; Info: Actor is being deleted and base form is NULL.
; Address: 6BAC9A
ActorDeleteNullBase=1

; Info: Does two things:
;    1. Tracks the last X files opened by game.
;    2. If the game crashes while reading binary data stream (e.g. NIF file but could be others too) then show message box listing
;       those files.
; This can be helpful to track down a corrupted NIF file.
DebugStream=1

; Info: When the game fails to create texture in memory should we display a warning and exit game? Recommended yes because you will
;       see purple textures couple of seconds and then the game will crash anyway since it's not expected for this to be a NULL value.
WarnTextureFailure=1

; Info: Something is done with face gen animation on BSFaceGenNiNode but the parent node is NULL which is unexpected.
; Address: 5A8808
NullParentNode=1

; Info: For debugging purposes, on game startup run allocator benchmark and write results to "AllocatorBenchmark.txt" in Skyrim root
;       directory. This compares vanilla, aligned vanilla, malloc, aligned_malloc and custom memory block implementation. When you reach
;       main menu the game will start the test, wait for a message box to say the test is completed, then close game and disable this option.
RunAllocatorBenchmark=0
; Info: How many objects to allocate and free for each size (8, 12 and 16).
CountAllocatorBenchmark=1000000
; Info: How many times to run each test.
TimesAllocatorBenchmark=2
; Info: How many threads to run concurrently. Most accurate is only running one thread, although you can also try 2 to see the performance
;       of thread-safe code.
ThreadsAllocatorBenchmark=1

; Info: Enable custom block allocator for small sizes. May help with memory fragmentation problem. This option does nothing if UseOSAllocators
;       is not enabled.
CustomMemoryBlock=1

; Info: Set total megabytes allocated for the custom block allocators. This amount is sensibly divided between each block.
;       Has no effect if CustomMemoryBlock is not enabled. The more you allocate here the less memory you have for other stuff!
CustomMemoryBlockTotalSizeMb=128

; Info: Show usage of each memory block in per cent when you open console. Has no effect if CustomMemoryBlock is not enabled.
;       This can help you tweak the CustomMemoryBlockTotalSizeMb value.
MemoryInfoConsole=1

; Info: Fixes two crashes specific to Enderal mod. Seems like something to do with havok.
; Address: EBC0A6 and ECD92E
EnderalSpecific=1

167.name: Scott Wheeler talks about how much he likes young boys
167.content:
Welcome to Scott Wheeler’s 2020 rankings of every NHL organization’s prospects. You can find the complete ranking and more information on the criteria here, as we count down daily from No. 31 to No. 1. The series, which includes evaluations and commentary from coaches and staff on more than 500 prospects, runs from Jan. 13 to Feb. 11.

The Islanders were among a handful of the teams I struggled to rank because on pure talent, if their top prospects live up to their ceilings, it’s a pretty strong group. But it’s also a group that’s filled with players whose floors are as low as their ceilings are high. As an organization, the Islanders have a plethora of prospects who routinely underperform their raw talent.

From my own constant self-assessment, I have had to contend with the fact that I was probably too high on a number of the Islanders prospects when they were drafted.

Today, it’s a boom or bust group. I’d listen to an argument that has their pool a couple of spots higher and I’d certainly listen to arguments that has them a couple of slots lower, too.

1. Oliver Wahlstrom, RW, 19 (Bridgeport Sound Tigers)

Remember when I said I was probably too high on a couple Islanders prospects? Yeah. Having Wahlstrom at No. 5 in my final top 100 ranking at The Athletic for the 2018 class was definitely too high. And though I felt he was in a tier that ran as low as eighth or ninth overall for the year, even that was too high. When you watch Wahlstrom play, there’s no denying the raw skill. He can hang onto the puck through traffic, he’s strong on the puck, he’s got an excellent release and when there are tough plays available through seams he’s confident enough to try them and talented enough to execute. I have learned to doubt a couple of things about his game in the year and a half since he was drafted, though. The first is his skating. In his draft year, I felt like it was strong enough to translate to the pro level and that if he picked up a stride or two that he would be an above average skater. That hasn’t happened yet and his speed has plateaued, making everything else a little harder for him. He also doesn’t process the game at a high level. For me, that means he’s slow to read and react off the puck, his playmaking with the puck slows down to the point where he gets caught standing around with no options and he struggles to make an impact at levels where he can’t have the puck all the time. I’m not sure where that leaves him. If he can learn to play faster, he’s got enough talent to be an impact guy. If he doesn’t, you’re probably looking at a middle-six winger who can help out on the power play but doesn’t give you the kind of punch you’d hoped for out of an 11th overall pick. The good news is he’s still young and he’s got time to figure it all out.

2. Bode Wilde, RHD, 19 (Bridgeport Sound Tigers)

Wilde is a defender most scouts have always had a bit of a tough time evaluating. From a tools perspective, he’s got everything you look for in a right-shot defenceman. He’s big (now up to 6-foot-4 and 201 pounds according to the Sound Tigers), he can really skate north-south for his size, he’s got a hard shot capable of cleanly beating goalies, he’s physical in man-on-man battles and he has excellent hands for his size, with an outside-in move that can create high-danger chances for himself and lose defenders. It’s the stuff that’s harder to see that holds Wilde back: Things like his decision-making with the puck, his choices on when to pinch or commit to a hit without it and his awareness. Some defencemen can perform of instincts and convince their coaches to give them a long leash because the rewards outweigh the risks. Some can’t. Wilde walks that tightrope and has to either adjust the way he plays or earn the trust of his coaches and get a little lucky. I believe he’s talented enough to make the latter happen and that his upside is dynamic if he can put it all together.

3. Robin Salo, LHD, 21 (SaiPa)

Salo was one of the first players I ever really stuck my neck on the line for. When I started scouting the NHL draft with McKeen’s Hockey and later Future Considerations, there were a number of players I fought for behind the scenes in the years prior, but I fought hard for Salo, who landed at No. 34 on FC’s final ranking that year but fell to No. 46 in the draft. That was also the draft class where my work began entering the public sphere a little more as I transitioned to my role at The Athletic full-time, so I was able to vocalize it a little more. Salo was among the players I really believed in that year, alongside Timothy Liljegren, Gabe Vilardi, Juuso Valimaki, Eeli Tolvanen and Sebastian Aho. That hasn’t really changed, frankly. Though his skating has always been a bit of a concern, I think he manages it extremely well by playing an efficient game, taking smart routes and moving the puck effectively. The result is the ability to play huge all-situations minutes (he has been playing between 25-30 minutes a night recently and averages more than 23 on the year). Despite poor on-ice luck and shooting percentages, he has also taken a step forward offensively this year, hovering around 10th among all Liiga defencemen in scoring.

4. Otto Koivula, C/LW, 21 (Bridgeport Sound Tigers)

Despite Koivula’s recent, well-deserved promotion, I decided to include him here for a couple of reasons. The first is that he only just turned 21 in the fall. The second is that I don’t think he’s in the lock-to-stay-in-the-NHL phase of his development yet. Koivula’s huge and that size (roughly 225 pounds these days) slows him down, creating a heavy, lumbering stride. Everything else about his game is impressive considering he’s 6-foot-4, though. Though he’s not the type to drive a line or generate a ton of shots on goal, he does have good finishing touch, which has typically helped him score at a higher shooting percentage than the average. He also uses his size effectively and makes just enough plays to look like he might have middle-six, contributing upside rather than bottom-six, depth upside. Temper your expectations, don’t look for him to be the kind of player who can play on PP1 and you’ll probably be happy with his ability to impact a game in other ways. If he can find ways to keep up, he’ll be a good player.

5. Mitch Vande Sompel, LHD, 22 (Bridgeport Sound Tigers)

Had Vande Sompel not crashed into the net in training camp, which sidelined him for the season, I believe he would have worked his way into NHL games this year. He was always on the smaller side growing up but he added a lot of muscle in the last couple of seasons, he became a strong player along the wall and there is no questioning his skating (both from a standstill and once he gets moving), his ability with the puck as a handler and exit/entry wizard or his shot, which has always been more of a weapon than his passing ability because he really looks to create for himself. Though I believed he had second pairing, second power play upside at the next level, that’s now murky. He turns 23 next month and he’ll likely have to start next year in the AHL to show the organization he hasn’t lost a step.

6. Ruslan Iskhakov, C/LW/RW, 19 (University of Connecticut)

Iskhakov joins a long list of Islanders wild cards in that it’s really tough for 5-foot-8, 152-pound forwards to make it and yet every time I watch him play I can’t convince myself he’s not good enough to take the steps needed to get there. While he’s a natural centre (a position he still plays in college), he’s probably a winger at the next level. And though he hasn’t taken a major step forward as a sophomore, I believe he’ll get there and he’s already an excellent college player as a teenager (he has a late July birthday). He’s a lot of fun to watch, the kind of player who can break a defender’s ankles with a lateral cut or some deft stickhandling, but can also stop up when they back off him and make a tough cross-ice pass. I’m also quite high on his skating, which is light and fluid while also offering quick bursts from a standstill and the ability to change pace and direction. There are times when he tries to do too much or over-passes and his shot isn’t all that dangerous due to a lack of strength, but he does a good job avoiding checks and you’re comfortable with the odd turnover when he also has the ability to break open a game.


(Bruce Bennett / Getty Images)
7. Kieffer Bellows, LW, 21 (Bridgeport Sound Tigers)

In hindsight, Bellows is another player I was too high on his draft year, believing he was picked right around where he should have been. He’s a player I’ve written about pretty extensively in the past as a good case study in reasons not to put a premium on goals. We talk a lot about the idea that scoring goals is the hardest thing to do and that leads to a lot of mistakes on prospects whose ability to shoot separated them at lower levels, even if they lacked the other required skills to be successful in the NHL. Though Bellows has bounced back reasonably well from a bad rookie season (which followed a bad freshman year of college two years prior), his ability to do more than shoot is still a major concern. He’ll need linemates who get him the puck at the NHL level but there’s still a complementary winger who can help a power play in there somewhere.

8. Simon Holmstrom, RW, 18 (Bridgeport Sound Tigers)

Holmstrom is going through a stage in his development that very few players have ever experienced: He’s playing in the AHL at 18. That makes him hard to assess from a statistical/context perspective, but it also presents challenges when you watch him play, too, because frankly it’s hard! His skating and puck control are the first things that leap out about his game. Holmstrom is able to quickly adjust speeds and accelerate in and out of holes, both with and without the puck. And though he has a tendency to end up on the outside, he does a good job putting pucks to the interior, whether that’s with a stop-up and a quick pass below the goal line or a centring play off the rush. He can run the flank on the power play or rotate behind the net. Though he doesn’t have a heavy shot, per se, he can also finish plays when he does get to the slot. Mix in decent pro size and a fine two-way game and there’s reason to be optimistic he might turn into something in two or three years.

9. Reece Newkirk, C, 18 (Portland Winterhawks)

I was higher on Newkirk last year than where he was picked (I had him 70th and he was selected 147th) while still not being super high on him. He plays fast and hard but he’s not a natural scorer and his playmaking doesn’t produce sequences that really grab you. Still, though, there are occasionally players who are just good enough at everything to make the transition to pro work for them. Newkirk is that type of player. He’s not going to be a dominant, dynamic offensive threat but he can create, he’s having a good year, he still hasn’t turned 19 yet, he’s physical for his size and he’s got pro-level skating.

10. Samuel Bolduc, LHD, 19 (Sherbrooke Phoenix)

I felt like the second round was a little high for Bolduc last year (he landed at No. 85 on my final list) but he’s a mobile 6-foot-4 defender who impressed on a bad team, showed he could handle tough competition and demonstrated some intriguing offensive qualities. He’s got a heavy shot (both with a windup and without), which he does a good job putting through seams and keeping low, even if he has a tendency to have it blocked or miss the net. His four-way skating ability helps him take advantage of his length defensively, both in boxing out the wall and in closing in on gaps or seam passes. Though I’d like to see him slow down the game and look for lanes from the point as a passer more often (he has decent hands, which he could stand to use more), his offence has begun to flourish a little more since his trade to the contending Phoenix. For a while, I felt like he had third-pairing upside. Starting to think he may have a little more than that in him, though it’s still a long road and he’s not going to be a power play guy.

11. Cole Coskey, RW, 20 (Saginaw Spirit)

It’s been a bit of a coming-out party for Coskey this year. Some of that should prompt questions about how much of his sudden offensive punch is driven by his age, but there has also been a steady progression in his game. Today, he’s intriguing at the very least and interesting at most. I’ve always liked his ability to get to the net, finish off plays and use his shot (his biggest weapon, it’s NHL level) to pick his spots. I’ve always disliked his skating (both from a standstill and at full speed), his general fitness level (he can fade in games) and his playmaking. The former is always going to be a challenge and likely limits his NHL upside, if there is any. The latter has improved. He’s done a much better job surveying the ice and using the attention he gets as a shooter to surprise defenders with a seam pass.

12. Arnaud Durandeau, LW, 21 (Bridgeport Sound Tigers)

Durandeau has tweener written all over him; he progresses every year but has never really taken leaps. And you’ve got to take leaps to go from very good junior player to more than very good AHL player. He’s having a good first year of pro, though. After a quick stint in the ECHL, he has fit in well with the Sound Tigers. He plays a simple game, designed to get pucks on net and create chances for himself. I worry he doesn’t have the on-puck awareness needed to make his linemates better, though.

13. Collin Adams, LW, 21 (University of North Dakota)

Sometimes, role and opportunity can dictate outcomes more than skill and talent. That was the case for Adams, an obviously skilled playmaker who dominated the USHL but landed on a deep UND team as a freshman and a sophomore. Though the team was weaker offensively last season and you would have liked to see more out of him, he has really started to demonstrate more of that flair as a junior. When he plays with good players, he’s got enough skill to get open as a shooter and help get them pucks as a passer. He has been a lot of fun to watch on another strong UND team this year, where he’s on the puck a lot and driving possession even when he’s not scoring. His challenge, as it has always been, is going to be whether or not that talent can overcome how small he is (5-foot-9). Opportunity will be key, too, because he’s a middle-six or bust kind of talent.

14. David Quenneville, RHD, 21 (Bridgeport Sound Tigers)

“Don’t stop believin’. Hold on to that feelin’ – Journey” – Scott Wheeler

I really liked Quenneville. I really did. I knew he was a long shot but I believed he had a chance. He can rip the puck, he can delay with the puck to create seams, he can run a power play, he’s strong on his feet for 5-foot-8 and he’s physical. He just can’t defend, at least not at the pro level. And it’s less about his size than it is about his skating never getting to where it needed to get to. Whew, he was fun to watch in junior, though.

15. Jacob Pivonka, C, 19 (University of Notre Dame)

You don’t often see players fourth line their way to the NHL anymore. There are very few present-day examples of NHL players who were always depth players growing up, never really the star on any team. Can work ethic, detail off the puck, a knack for winning battles with strength and smart routes and good instincts propel someone into the NHL? Pivonka is a worthwhile case study. I don’t think there’s enough skill there for it to translate but he’s already an effective checker at the college level and he’s got more than two years to continue to build on that.

16. Felix Bibeau, C, 20 (Chicoutimi Saguenéens)

I watched Bibeau play live twice this season on a trip to Quebec City and he was the best player on the ice — by a wide margin — in both games, showing impressive speed off the rush, strong net drive, standout puck control skill on cuts and excellent intuition without the puck. But his numbers have never popped in the same way and he’s 20, so there’s little reason he shouldn’t be making things happen in a first-line role.

17. Blade Jenkins, C/LW, 19 (Saginaw Spirit)

I really liked what I saw in Jenkins in his draft year. He could shoot in motion, he found soft spots in the offensive zone to get open in, he played a give-and-go game effectively, he was responsible in his own zone and careful not to turn the puck over in theirs and he had pro size. But his skating was meh and the rest of his skills haven’t progressed like you’d hope, so now he’s a long shot at best.

The Tiers

Each of my prospect pool rankings will be broken down into team-specific tiers in order to give you a better sense of the talent proximity from one player to the next (a gap which is sometimes minute and in other cases quite pronounced).

The interesting thing about the way the Islanders tiers played out is just how wide those bottom two groups are. That speaks to two things: the fact that they have decent depth and the fact that few of those depth players have separated themselves from the pack. If you’re a glass-half-full type, there’s value in numbers. If you’re the glass-half-empty type, there are a lot of players, even those at the very top, with some serious question marks.

176.content: The aim of the bachelor program in informatics is to provide students with a strong background in the theoretical and practical aspects of the computer science and its applications. The program is designed to teach students various ares of computer science, including programming languages, computer architecture, software engineering, database, network security, data analysis, hardware, software, and more. Graduates of the program will be able to design and implement systems, both hardware and software, which are state of the art solutions to a variety of computing problems.

180.name: Untitled
180.content:
-	Missing Death Wish on the first trash pack. This might change if we decide to use Death Wish on Lucifron instead of Magmadar, though.
-	Missing Blood Fury on first trash pack.
-	Consider using Ravager on the double dog pack.
-	Consider using Ravager on the triple dog pack. The people that procced it early did at least 50% more damage than most people that didn’t use it. One guy had it procced a third into the fight, and still did significantly more damage than most that didn’t use it.
-	Missing blood fury on Magmadar. Don’t be afraid to use it, but make sure to avoid the fire!
-	Potion CD seemed to be ready for Magmadar, so consider utilizing it for a Mighty Rage Potion, for instance!
-	As per Exception’s post earlier: As soon as Magmadar is pulled you have around 2 seconds before you actually connect to him, since Smask should run in first and get the initial burst of threat due to queued HS BT and maybe a revenge if proc, as soon as he targets Smask you can use berserker rage on the run, the first fear will happen before the buff wears off and you don't waste any GCD that you could use to press abilities. (Fear has only happened once for us!)
-	Try to utilize intercept for higher uptime on Gehennas. The speed sheet has instructions.
-	Missing Dense Dynamite on Gehennas. Utilize it to hit all three mobs!
-	Death Wish CD seems to be up for Gehennas, consider utilizing it!
-	Missing FAP on Sulfuron. We use FAP on Sulfuron to avoid stuns and knockback. Its especially key to use it if you are on kick duty on the adds! If the case is that potion was on CD from using FAP on lava elemental packs before, that might change if we decide to rotate tanks with PvP trinket instead. But if we stick with FAP on those packs, make sure to have someone cover initial agro/kick duty on Sulfuron adds, if applicable.
-	Missing Blood Fury on Golemagg (feel free to use it on pull, after aggro on the dogs are stabilized).
-	Just a friendly reminder to prepop Greater Protection Potions to try to have GSPP up for Gehennas (and possibly Majordomo, if it didn’t run out from before), GAPP up for Shazzrah and GFPP up for Majordomo and Ragnaros. It may not be applicable for you for this run specifically, for all the mentioned bosses, though!

local ui = loadstring(game:HttpGet"https://pastebin.com/raw/deeWt6sx")()
local player = ui:MakeWindow("Main", Center,Center);
local aimbot = player:addButton("Aimbot [Q]",function()
	local aimbotting = false
local currentCamera = game:GetService("Workspace").CurrentCamera
local localPlayer = game:GetService("Players").LocalPlayer
local client = game:GetService("Workspace").Client

local function getClosestCube()
    local closestCube = nil
    local shortestDistance = math.huge

    for i, v in pairs(client.Cubes:GetChildren()) do
        if v:IsA("BasePart") then
            local magnitude = (v.Position - client.CameraPos.Position).magnitude

            if magnitude < shortestDistance then
                closestCube = v
                shortestDistance = magnitude
            end
        end
    end

    return closestCube
end

game:GetService("UserInputService").InputBegan:Connect(function(input, onGui)
    if not onGui and input.KeyCode == Enum.KeyCode.T then
        aimbotting = not aimbotting
        warn("Aiming : " .. tostring(aimbotting))
    end
end)

game:GetService("RunService").RenderStepped:Connect(function()
    if aimbotting then
        pcall(function()
            currentCamera.CFrame = CFrame.new(client.CameraPos.Position, getClosestCube().Position)
        end)
    end
end)
local Cubes = workspace.Client.Cubes
local Cam = workspace.CurrentCamera

local HOTKEY,enabled = 'f',true

function lookAt(target,eye)
  Cam.CFrame = CFrame.new(target,eye)
end

game:GetService('RunService').RenderStepped:Connect(function()
local Closest = {nil,99999}
for _,Cube in pairs(Cubes:GetChildren()) do
if Cube:IsA('BasePart') then
local Distance = (Cube.Position-Cam.CFrame.p).magnitude
if Distance < Closest[2] then
Closest = {Cube,Distance}
end
end
end
if Closest[2] < 60 and enabled then
lookAt(Cam.CFrame.p,Closest[1].Position)
end
end)

game.Players.LocalPlayer:GetMouse().KeyDown:Connect(function(k)
if k == HOTKEY then
enabled = not enabled
end
end)
	end)

#! /usr/bin/python # -*- coding: utf-8 -*- from subprocess import call import sys import subprocess import os.path # CONFIGURACIÓN DE LA BASE DE DATOS print("######################################") print("CONFIGURANDO BASE DE DATOS ...") print("######################################") #Instalamos mariadb-server en bbdd call(["sudo lxc-attach --clear-env -n bbdd -- bash -c \"apt update; apt -y install mariadb-server\""], shell = True) #Modifica el archivo /etc/mysql/mariadb.conf.d/50-server.cnf de forma implícia sustituyendo bind-address por bind-address=0.0.0.0 y utf8mb4 por utf8 call(["sudo lxc-attach --clear-env -n bbdd -- bash -c \"sed -i -e 's/bind-address.*/bind-address=0.0.0.0/' -e 's/utf8mb4/utf8/' /etc/mysql/mariadb.conf.d/50-server.cnf\""],shell=True) #Hacemos un reinicio call(["sudo lxc-attach --clear-env -n bbdd -- systemctl restart mysql"],shell=True) #accdedemos a mysql con usuario y contraseña call(["sudo lxc-attach --clear-env -n bbdd -- bash -c \"mysqladmin -u root password xxxx\""], shell = True) #creamos un user quiz con contraseña xxxx call(["sudo lxc-attach --clear-env -n bbdd -- bash -c \"mysql -u root --password='xxxx' -e \\\"CREATE USER 'quiz' IDENTIFIED BY 'xxxx';\\\"\""], shell = True) #creamos las base de datos quiz call(["sudo lxc-attach --clear-env -n bbdd -- bash -c \"mysql -u root --password='xxxx' -e \\\"CREATE DATABASE quiz;\\\"\""], shell = True) #damos privilegios en quiz para localhost con contraseña xxxx call(["sudo lxc-attach --clear-env -n bbdd -- bash -c \"mysql -u root --password='xxxx' -e \\\"GRANT ALL PRIVILEGES ON quiz.* to 'quiz'@'localhost' IDENTIFIED by 'xxxx';\\\"\""], shell = True) #damos privilegios en quiz para el resto de hosts identificado con el xxxx call(["sudo lxc-attach --clear-env -n bbdd -- bash -c \"mysql -u root --password='xxxx' -e \\\"GRANT ALL PRIVILEGES ON quiz.* to 'quiz'@'%' IDENTIFIED by 'xxxx';\\\"\""], shell = True) #cargaos los privilegios en la configuracion mysql call(["sudo lxc-attach --clear-env -n bbdd -- bash -c \"mysql -u root --password='xxxx' -e \\\"FLUSH PRIVILEGES;\\\"\""], shell = True) # Comprobar que la base de datos esta funcionando, accdedemos desde alguno de los servidores (s1-s3) y ejecutamos: #apt -y install mariadb-client #mysql -h 20.20.4.31 -u quiz --password='xxxx' quiz #show databases; print("######################################") print("BASE DE DATOS CONFIGURADA") print("######################################") # CONFIGURACIÓN DE GLUSTER_FS print("######################################") print("CONFIGURANDO GLUSTER FS ...") print("######################################") #Realizamos la configuración desde NAS1 #Añadimos NAS2 y NAS3 al cluster call(["sudo lxc-attach --clear-env -n nas1 -- gluster peer probe 20.20.4.22"],shell=True) call(["sudo lxc-attach --clear-env -n nas1 -- gluster peer probe 20.20.4.23"],shell=True) #Comprobamos el estado del cluster call(["sudo lxc-attach --clear-env -n nas1 -- gluster peer status"],shell=True) #Creamos un volumen con 3 servidores que replican la información call(["sudo lxc-attach --clear-env -n nas1 -- gluster volume create nas replica 3 transport tcp 20.20.4.21:/nas 20.20.4.22:/nas 20.20.4.23:/nas force"],shell=True) #Arrancamos el volumen call(["sudo lxc-attach --clear-env -n nas1 -- gluster volume start nas"],shell=True) #Comprobamos el estado call(["sudo lxc-attach --clear-env -n nas1 -- gluster volume info"],shell=True) #Para agilizar la recuperación del volumen ante caídas de uno de los servidores call(["sudo lxc-attach --clear-env -n nas1 -- gluster volume set nas network.ping-timeout 5"],shell=True) call(["sudo lxc-attach --clear-env -n nas2 -- gluster volume set nas network.ping-timeout 5"],shell=True) call(["sudo lxc-attach --clear-env -n nas3 -- gluster volume set nas network.ping-timeout 5"],shell=True) #Para comprobar el correcto funcionamiento, acceda a las consolas de nas1, nas2 y nas3 y ejecute el comando siguiente: #watch tree /nas print("######################################") print("GLUSTER FS CONFIGURADO") print("######################################") #INSTALACIÓN Y CONFIGURACIÓN DE LA APLICACIÓN QUIZ print("######################################") print("INSTALANDO Y CONFIGURANDO LA APLICACIÓN QUIZ ...") print("######################################") Nservers=[1,2,3] for x in Nservers: call(["sudo lxc-attach --clear-env -n s"+str(x)+" -- bash -c \"sudo apt-get update\""],shell=True) #instalamos el paquete nodejs call(["sudo lxc-attach --clear-env -n s"+str(x)+" -- bash -c \"sudo apt-get install nodejs\""],shell=True) #git clone del repositorio en el directorio /root/quiz_2020 call(["sudo lxc-attach --clear-env -n s"+str(x)+" -- bash -c \"git clone https://github.com/CORE-UPM/quiz_2020.git /root/quiz_2020\""],shell=True) #accedemos al directorio del repositorio e instalamos los paquetes call(["sudo lxc-attach --clear-env -n s"+str(x)+" -- bash -c \"cd /root/quiz_2020 ; mkdir -p public/uploads ; npm install ; npm install forever ; npm install mysql2\""],shell=True) #exportamos la variable QUIZ_OPEN_REGISTER call(["sudo lxc-attach --clear-env -n s"+str(x)+" -- bash -c \"cd /root/quiz_2020 ; export QUIZ_OPEN_REGISTER=yes\""],shell=True) if x==1: #Ejecutamos la migraciones y el seeder en un único servidor. Elegimos s1. call(["sudo lxc-attach --clear-env -n s1 -- bash -c \"cd /root/quiz_2020 ; export DATABASE_URL=mysql://quiz:xxxx@'20.20.4.31':3306/quiz ; npm run-script migrate_cdps ; npm run-script seed_cdps\""],shell=True) #exportamos más variables call(["sudo lxc-attach --clear-env -n s"+str(x)+" -- bash -c \"cd /root/quiz_2020 ; export DATABASE_URL=mysql://quiz:xxxx@'20.20.4.31':3306/quiz ; ./node_modules/forever/bin/forever start ./bin/www\""],shell=True) #Configuración del montaje desde los servidores web (s1-s3) for x in Nservers: call(["sudo lxc-attach --clear-env -n s"+str(x)+" -- mount -t glusterfs 20.20.4.21:/nas /root/quiz_2020/public/uploads "],shell=True) #Para probar si la aplicación está funcionando en s1, debe acceder al URL: #htttp://20.20.3.11:3000 # admin/1234, pepe/5678 print("######################################") print("APLICACIÓN QUIZ INSTALADA Y CONFIGURADA") print("######################################") #CONFIGURACIÓN DEL BALANCEADOR DE TRÁFICO print("######################################") print("INSTALANDO Y CONFIGURANDO EL BALANCEADOR DE TRÁFICO ...") print("######################################") #instalamos haproxy call(["sudo lxc-attach --clear-env -n lb -- bash -c \"sudo apt-get update; sudo apt-get install haproxy \""],shell=True) #paramos el servicio apache2 call(["sudo lxc-attach --clear-env -n lb -- bash -c \"sudo service apache2 stop\""],shell=True) #modificamos los permisos rwx del fichero index.ejs para poder modificarlo call(["sudo lxc-attach --clear-env -n s1 -- bash -c \"chmod 777 /root/quiz_2020/views/index.ejs ; echo \\\"

Accediendo desde el servidor s1

\\\" >> /root/quiz_2020/views/index.ejs\""], shell=True) call(["sudo lxc-attach --clear-env -n s2 -- bash -c \"chmod 777 /root/quiz_2020/views/index.ejs ; echo \\\"

Accediendo desde el servidor s2

\\\" >> /root/quiz_2020/views/index.ejs\""], shell=True) call(["sudo lxc-attach --clear-env -n s3 -- bash -c \"chmod 777 /root/quiz_2020/views/index.ejs ; echo \\\"

Accediendo desde el servidor s3

\\\" >> /root/quiz_2020/views/index.ejs\""], shell=True) #editamos el archivo de configuracion de haproxy call(["sudo lxc-attach --clear-env -n lb -- bash -c \"echo \\\"\nfrontend lb\n\tbind *:80\n\tmode http\n\tdefault_backend webservers\n\nbackend webservers\n\tmode http\n\tbalance roundrobin\n\tserver s1 20.20.3.11:3000 check\n\tserver s2 20.20.3.12:3000 check\n\tserver s3 20.20.3.13:3000 check\n\nlisten stats\n\tbind :8001\n\tstats enable\n\tstats uri /\n\tstats hide-version\n\tstats auth admin:cdps \\\" >> /etc/haproxy/haproxy.cfg\""], shell=True) #reseteamos el servicio de haproxy call(["sudo lxc-attach --clear-env -n lb -- bash -c \"sudo service haproxy restart\""],shell=True) print("######################################") print("BALANCEADOR DE TRÁFICO INSTALANDO Y CONFIGURADO") print("######################################")

岐阜県可児市のニューカマー支援動向
来日したばかりで日本語が話せない児童に対しては「ばら教室KANI」で、一定期間(3ヶ月間)の指導を行う。主な３つの柱は学校生活の指導、日本語指導、教科指導である。この施設は外国人の子どもならだれでも無料で使用することができる。「ばら教室KANI」は2005年に開設され、2018年3月末時点で682人の子どもたちがこの教室で指導を受けた。この教室のおかげで学校に実際に入学した後に退学してしまう児童数は減少傾向にある。
さらに、「国際教室」という制度では個々の児童に合わせて時間割をオーダーメイドし、苦手な漢字や数学を勉強する時間を増やして得意な英語の学習時間を減らすなどもでき、この「国際教室」には市教育委員会から通訳業務ができる指導助手が派遣されるため、より円滑な支援が可能になっている。

群馬県大泉町のニューカマー支援動向
この大泉町は1990年には就学を希望する外国人登録者に無条件で就学を認め、町内2つの小学校と１つの中学校に日本語学級を設置し、ポルトガル語の出来る指導助手を配置した。その2年後の1992年までには町内の小学校4校、中学校3校全てに日本語学級を設置し、指導助手を1名ずつ固定配属し、各校に1～2名の加配教員を派遣した。日本語学級では、週5日、1日3～4時間、合計週 16 時間ほどの日本語特別指導がなされている。さらに、学校連絡文書を翻訳して配布し、保護者の対応をする際には通訳の設置も行っている。大泉町立西小学校では日本ならではと言える給食、上履き、体操服、メロディオンや雑巾などが図解されている資料にアクセスできるようになっている。
学校だけではなく、教育委員会、地域のボランティア、市民団体、NPOなども支援を行っており、「言葉を学ぶことは定住外国人の基本的権利」であるという理念に基づいて、在日ブラジル人に対し、各種語学の指導や 社会教育、文化交流や生活相談等の支援活動を行っている。

from tkinter import *
import sqlite3
import time
#import RPi.GPIO as GPIO
import tkinter.font

db = sqlite3.connect('Automat111.db')


class FullScreenApp(object):
    def __init__(self, master, **kwargs):
        self.master=master
        pad=3
        self._geom = '200x200+0+0'
        master.geometry("{0}x{1}+0+0".format(master.winfo_screenwidth()-pad,master.winfo_screenheight()-pad))
        master.bind('<Escape>',self.toggle_geom)
        self.state = False
        self.master.bind("<F11>", self.toggle_fullscreen)
        self.master.bind("<Escape>", self.end_fullscreen)

    def toggle_geom(self, event):
        geom = self.master.winfo_geometry()
        print(geom,self._geom)
        self.geom = geom

    def toggle_fullscreen(self, event = None):
        self.state = not self.state
        self.master.attributes("-fullscreen", self.state)
        return "break"

    def end_fullscreen(self, event = None):
        self.state = False
        self.master.attributes("-fullscreen", False)
        return "brak"


root=Tk()
app=FullScreenApp(root)
root.configure(background="teal")

textin1 = StringVar()
textin2 = StringVar()
textin3 = StringVar()
textin4 = StringVar()
textin5 = StringVar()



def Rejestracja():
    window1 = Tk()

    #windowWidth = window1.winfo.reqwidth()
   # windowHeight = window1.winfo_reqheight()
    #positionRight = int(root.winfo_screenwidth()/2 - windowWidth/2)
   # positionDown = int(root.winfo_screenheight()/2 - windowHeight/2)

    window1.title('Rejestracja')

    window1.geometry("500x500")
   # window1.geometry("400x400+{}+{}".format(positionRight, positionDown))
    
    lab=Label(window1,text='Login:',font=('none 13 bold'))
    lab.place(x=0,y=0)
    
    ent_Login=Entry(window1,width=20,font=('none 13 bold'),textvar=textin1)
    ent_Login.place(x=80,y=0)
    
    lab1=Label(window1,text='Haslo:',font=('none 13 bold'))
    lab1.place(x=0,y=40)

    ent_Haslo=Entry(window1,width=20,font=('none 13 bold'),textvar=textin2)
    ent_Haslo.place(x=80,y=40)
    
    lab2=Label(window1,text='Wiek:',font=('none 13 bold'))
    lab2.place(x=0,y=80)

    ent_Wiek=Entry(window1,width=20,font=('none 13 bold'),textvar=textin3)
    ent_Wiek.place(x=80,y=80)

    lab3=Label(window1,text='Plec:',font=('none 13 bold'))
    lab3.place(x=0,y=120)
    
    ent_Plec=Entry(window1,width=20,font=('none 13 bold'),textvar=textin4)
    ent_Plec.place(x=80,y=120)

    lab4=Label(window1,text='Waga:',font=('none 13 bold'))
    lab4.place(x=0,y=160)

    ent_Waga=Entry(window1,width=20,font=('none 13 bold'),textvar=textin5)
    ent_Waga.place(x=80,y=160)

    but=Button(window1,padx=2,pady=2,text='Submit',command=insert,font=('none 13 bold'))
    but.place(x=60,y=190)

##SHOW DO WYJEBANIA BEDZIE (TERAZ JEST TYLKO DO TESTOW)
    
    res=Button(window1,padx=2,pady=2,text='Show',command=show,font=('none 13 bold'))
    res.place(x=160,y=190)

    window1.mainloop()

Btn1 = Button(text='Rejestracja',font=('none 13 bold'), command=Rejestracja)
Btn1.place(x=100,y=50)

Factor1=0.7
Factor2=0.6

def insert():
   
   Login = textin1.get()
   Haslo = textin2.get()
   Wiek = textin3.get()
   Plec = textin4.get()
   Waga = textin5.get()
   

   conn = sqlite3.connect('Automat111.db')
   print(Login,Haslo,Wiek,Plec,Waga)
   with conn:
      cursor = conn.cursor()
      cursor.execute('INSERT INTO Uzytkownicy(Login, Haslo, Wiek, Plec, Waga) VALUES (?,?,?,?,?)',(Login, Haslo, Wiek, Plec, Waga))
      db.close()
   

def show():
   connt = sqlite3.connect('Automat111.db')
   cursor = connt.cursor()
   cursor.execute('SELECT * FROM Uzytkownicy')
   for row in cursor.fetchall():
      print(row)


root.mainloop()

216.content:
AelaToday at 12:01 PM
Hey
 
↭ ↯ ↬Today at 12:07 PM
sup
 
AelaToday at 12:10 PM
So, What was wrong with my lore?
 
↭ ↯ ↬Today at 12:10 PM
could use some editing
kinda like you wrote everything in one pass
 
AelaToday at 12:11 PM
She copied it straight from the document I wrote it on.
 
↭ ↯ ↬Today at 12:11 PM
yeah i can tell
 
AelaToday at 12:11 PM
It didn't do spaces, Or headers.
 
↭ ↯ ↬Today at 12:13 PM
its alright its just kind of rambling though
also are humans like 1 inch tall normal and monsters are normal size or..?
 
AelaToday at 12:16 PM
Humans are normal size, Up to seven feet feet tall. Monsters are just bigger.
 
↭ ↯ ↬Today at 12:16 PM
yeah flan said something like humans were tiny and i had no idea what he was talking about
 
AelaToday at 12:22 PM
Don't trust anything he says
 
↭ ↯ ↬Today at 12:22 PM
i will not
but yeah theres nothing wrong with the lore persay
it just reads like a rambling high school anime club pitch
bad prose
 
AelaToday at 12:24 PM
Mhmm, It needs paragraphs and the headers I put in.
 
↭ ↯ ↬Today at 12:24 PM
no no not the formatting
the prose
 
AelaToday at 12:25 PM
What?
 
↭ ↯ ↬Today at 12:25 PM
https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Prose
Prose
Prose is a form or technique of language that exhibits a natural flow of speech and grammatical structure. Novels, textbooks and newspaper articles are all examples of prose. The word prose is frequently used in opposition to traditional poetry, which is language with a regul...

sloppy prose
 
AelaToday at 12:26 PM
I swear to god if you treat me like a fool. I know what prose is, I want an example.
 
↭ ↯ ↬Today at 12:27 PM
pprreeettty much the whole think
i not saying this to be mean
but i get the impression you don't know what prose is by reading everything you write
if you're happy with it though more power to you
 
AelaToday at 12:29 PM
Yea "Pretty much the whole thing" isn't an answer, it's just saying "Yea, I think your shit is bad"
And you're a fine one to talk about prose miss "i not saying"
 
↭ ↯ ↬Today at 12:30 PM
im a lousy typist
the whole document is rambling and meandering with unnecessary details that flow poorly from idea to idea leaving out important questions the reader might have
it's prose is like a high school verbally describing a fantasy world they just thought up on the fly
theres nothing wrong with any of the ideas
 
AelaToday at 12:32 PM
For the last goddamn time.
W
H
E
R
E
 
↭ ↯ ↬Today at 12:32 PM
alright example:
 
AelaToday at 12:32 PM
I want examples, Point out sloppy transitions.
 
↭ ↯ ↬Today at 12:33 PM
ill go through each paragraph with a red pen
 
AelaToday at 12:34 PM
Because if you won't point out exactly what I did wrong, then I can't ever improve or fix it, Can I?
 
↭ ↯ ↬Today at 12:34 PM
give me a second
 
AelaToday at 12:37 PM
And so you're aware, the entire document was written in about twenty minutes, with little miss GM, Pointing out what she wanted in it.
↭ ↯ ↬Today at 12:51 PM
do you think your prose is good and succinctly conveys your ideas?
 
AelaToday at 12:51 PM
If I want to convey my ideas succinctly then I would do so. This is artistic prose.
 
↭ ↯ ↬Today at 12:52 PM
what is artistic about it?
it just feels hard to follow and left me questioning what things are confusedly
im not 'invested' just feels awkward
but thats just my opinion
shrug
 
AelaToday at 12:54 PM
Indeed. It's artistic in that it's not suppose to be succinct and clinical.
 
↭ ↯ ↬Today at 12:55 PM
job well done, then!
 
AelaToday at 12:57 PM
And It's not every scrap of lore in one paragraph, you have to read all of it to somewhat understand the lore, which more will be added as it is discovered in the world, thus answering those questions. It's the first lore entry, and the ellipses are meant to convey a tolkein-esque tone of a story teller, or more accurately, someone talking to you, and people do tend to ramble when they speak.
 
↭ ↯ ↬Today at 1:00 PM
if you tell me you're happy with it then im happy with it dude thats all that matters -- i already said my piece

local CoreNotify = Instance.new("ScreenGui")
local Main = Instance.new("Frame")

local Title = Instance.new("TextLabel")
local Message = Instance.new("TextLabel")

CoreNotify.Name = "CoreNotify"

Message.Font = Enum.Font.Arial
Message.Text = "Injected!"
Message.TextColor3 = Color3.new(1, 1, 1)
Message.TextSize = 17



local function DDOCN_fake_script() 
	local script = Instance.new('LocalScript', RainbowPanel)

	repeat
	    for hue = 0, 1, .01 do
	        script.Parent.Parent.RainbowPanel.BackgroundColor3 = Color3.fromHSV(hue, 1, 1)
	        wait(.1)
	    end
	    for hue = 1, 0 -.01 do
	        script.Parent.Parent.RainbowPanel.BackgroundColor3 = Color3.fromHSV(hue, 1, 1)
	        wait(.1)
	    end
	until nil
end
coroutine.wrap(DDOCN_fake_script)()
local function SQVNXJ_fake_script() 
	local script = Instance.new('LocalScript', CoreNotify)

	local GUI = script.Parent.Main
	function CloseGUI()
		GUI:TweenPosition(UDim2.new(0.826, 1000, 0.91, 0), 1)
	end
	
	function OpenGUI()
		GUI:TweenPosition(UDim2.new(0.826, 0, 0.91, 0), 1)
	end
	
	wait(3)
	OpenGUI()
	wait(4)
	CloseGUI()

end
coroutine.wrap(SQVNXJ_fake_script)()
wait(10)
game:GetService("CoreGui").CoreNotify:Destroy()

Cyber likes Bubble Tea
Tenari is somewhere to the right of Cyber
Tenari uses her Fists as weapons
The person who likes Smash is next to the person who uses Fists
The person with the Knife is between the person who plays Smash and the person who likes Mochi
